snippet.textDisplay:
For the people splurting out random crap about saffron and lamb. If you spend 30 dollars on Saffron, it will last you literally the entire year feeding a family of 6. On a cost per meal analysis, that is EXTREMELY cheap. As for referencing lamb. Not everyone lives in the U.S lol. Lamb is dirt cheap over where he's at. It's near the equivalent, if not cheaper, of getting beef in Texas/Nebraska. Vanilla is also fairly cheap in relation to how much of it you use. A few specks of a bean ((literally a few specks of it)) can season an entire pot of food. Even with liberal use it'll last you a good 6 months.

Mackeral: Extremely cheap fish, arguably one of the healthiest + sustainable too.

Prawn+ pork: Also dirt cheap

Avocado: Spend 4 dollars for 2 of them in land locked zones. 2 avocados will last around a week. They're also very filling and jam packed with nutrients. Can very easily meal prep 7 different meals with just two avocados.

Star Anise: You can plop one, maybe even two star anise into a GIANT POT THAT WILL FEED YOU FOR 3+ WEEKS.


All in all, I can say with 100% confidence that Ramsay's meals were exceptionally cheap + on the healthy end . . . which is unique in the world of cheap food.


You guys spend more on cheap cigarettes + random gas station garbage a month than you would utilizing the techniques he demonstrated here.

snippet.textDisplay:
A lot of people complaining about prices, let me try and ease your minds a bit. Not their minds, they are already gone.. but anyone who happens to see my comment I guess.

Saffron: It can be very daunting when you see huge prices like 100USD next to 1 ounce at a store near you. But we need to put it into perspective a bit. Per recipe you are likely to only use a single pinch. Realistically that is probably somewhere around 0.003 grams? One teaspoon is about 0.5 grams. So you can imagine what a pinch of that would be. Your scale would not even be able to register it unless you had a specific scale for it. All in all, you can buy about a full gram of saffron for about 10 bucks on Amazon (use the Honey app any maybe get a discount) and that should last you 20 pinches at least. Which means 20 dishes. With more searching you may be able to find a smaller amount, enough for a few recipes for much much less. And you can double check stores near you or other online stores for cheaper prices. It really is not expensive when put into perspective. Its like complaining that 50 lbs of pillows is expensive.. you don't need that many pillows. Weight does not equal quantity.

Dijon Mustard: Honestly stop it.. if you can afford regular mustard you can afford dijon. If by some circumstance dijon is a few dollars higher in your area and you don't want to pay a few dollars higher.. just use the regular mustard. You are allowed to make compromises.

Lamb: Now the first thing people think is lamb chops which can reach 20 bucks a pound. But if you listen carefully he says lamb steaks! It was most likely a different cut of the lamb. I would guess either a shoulder, a shank, maybe a loin. Probably was 9 to 12 dollars per pound. Keep in mind this is the main ingredient, so of course its going to cost the most.

When you consider that this video is not generally meant for giant family dinners.. of course you are not going to make 20 dishes. The idea is.. maybe you have someone you love and you want to cook dinner for them? 2 dishes, the ingredient cost, no more than 25 bucks for what goes into the pan. Its a nice gourmet dinner that going to a restaurant would cost you upwards of 60 dollars.. I would consider that a budget.

Out of all of these dishes, the one I find funny that nobody complains about are the rice balls. And for good reason. They probably cost less than 5 bucks in ingredients per plate of 4, and you will fill up so easy on them. So even if you have a problem with the other dishes.. Don't just rag on the entire video when you have something that looks delicious and most likely costs less than kraft dinner, to make.

All in all, you are allowed to substitute to meet your own budgets.. but I refuse to believe that you people who pay a monthly internet fee cannot afford to make any of these dishes once in a blue moon. He is not suggesting you make it every night, jesus. If you really cant afford this, maybe you should reconsider having an internet until you are more financially stable?

Its a nice gourmet dinner that going to a restaurant would cost you upwards of 60 dollars.. I would consider that a budget.

Out of all of these dishes, the one I find funny that nobody complains about are the rice balls. And for good reason. They probably cost less than 5 bucks in ingredients per plate of 4, and you will fill up so easy on them. So even if you have a problem with the other dishes.. Don't just rag on the entire video when you have something that looks delicious and most likely costs less than kraft dinner, to make. 

All in all, you are allowed to substitute to meet your own budgets.. but I refuse to believe that you people who pay a monthly internet fee cannot afford to make any of these dishes once in a blue moon. He is not suggesting you make it every night, jesus. If you really cant afford this, maybe you should reconsider having an internet until you are more financially stable?
